<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-638-631  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 638 631.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 15 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Reference Point offers environmental database. (The InternationalNetwork for Environmental Policy's international environmentaldatabase)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data basesInformation servicesEnvironmental ProtectionInformation Storage and RetrievalInternational Network for Environmental Policy.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>REFERENCE POINT OFFERS ENVIRONMENTAL DATABASE TEANECK, NEW JERSEY, U.S.A.,andO;1990 OCT 15 (NB) -- The International Network for Environmental Policy andits international environmental database won't be online until next year.andO;The delay is due to a change in the design of the system, from a singlehost-based mainframe to a distributed computing environment.andM;John Harris, who is helping put the database together, told Newsbytes thatfoundation grants are being sought for start-up costs, but it's expected thedatabase will eventually be self-funding, at about $25 per hour of access.andO;&quot;The core database will be a master directory of information resources --people, organizations, bibliographic references to other information systemsand databases,&quot; he said.andM;Of the new design, he said, &quot;There will still be a central host, but some ofthe databases will be parallel at each node.andP;  Conference notes or bulletinboards will be parallel, the information directory will be parallel, and somedatabases will be maintained in some localities, not others.andP;  Initially we'llhave 5-6 nodes.andP;  Eventually we'll have hundreds.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19901012/Press Contact: INEP, John Harris, 301- 596-2740)</TEXT></DOC>